/eot. (It wasn't quite time for game theory today, so it's evil AI discussion)
It's the everyday AI doing everyday discrimination, such as differential pricing, that is the big problem ahead of us.
I'm afraid that the focus on evil AI trying to kill humankind, or self-driving cars solving trolley problems wrong, is misleading.
The challenge here is that the devs can always claim that it's some other feature that explains price discrimination.
But there are countless other cues: you don't need norwegian pages translated? regularly buy injeera? etc.
How do you tell if AI is, say, racist? That it charges black (or white) people more? Devs might swear that they don't take race as an input.
It's easier, but still very hard, to do an end-to-end test on the outcomes.
It's impossible to define "AI." If the web is any guide, future AI will consist of blobs of learning algos slapped together haphazardly.
But I doubt "regulating AI" is the way to go. Much better to regulate the outcome than the methods used.
Worse, it might not even be aware of what it's doing. Perhaps it has not been fed race as an input, but it has learned to pick up other cues
It could be discriminating because of your past history, race, belief system, gender, or any other thing that you have no control over.
Now imagine the same, except the AI cannot enunciate what the policy is. Just that it has been trained not to do the sensible thing.
I'm sure you all have faced a service worker who says "I'm sorry, this is our policy."
